& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Transcatheter left atrial appendage (LAA) closure is an alternative to long-term anticoagulation therapy in selected patients with nonvalvular atrial fibrillation who have an increased risk for stroke. LAA closure devices can be implanted by means of either an endocardial or a combined endocardial and epicardial approach. Preprocedural imaging is key to identifying contraindications, accurately sizing the device, and minimizing complications. Transesophageal echocardiography (TEE) has been the reference standard imaging modality to assess the anatomy for LAA closure and to provide intraprocedural guidance. However, CT has emerged as a less-invasive alternative to TEE for pre- and postprocedural imaging. CT is comparable to TEE for exclusion of thrombus but is superior to TEE for the delineation of complex LAA anatomy, measurement for device sizing, and evaluation of pulmonary venous and extracardiac structures. CT provides accurate measurements of the LAA ostial diameter, landing zone diameter, and LAA length, which are vital for accurate sizing of the device. CT allows evaluation of the relationship with the pulmonary veins and other adjacent structures that can be injured during the procedure. CT also simulates procedural fluoroscopic angles and provides evaluation of the interatrial septum, which is punctured during LAA closure. CT also provides a more convenient method for the evaluation of postprocedural complications such as incomplete closure, peridevice leaking, device-related thrombus, and device dislodgement.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200136">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200136">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Commonly used transcatheter LAAC devices. Endocardial devices include the Watchman, Watchman FLX, and Amplatzer Amulet. The Lariat is the commonly used combined endocardial-epicardial device."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig1.jpeg" height="500" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Commonly used transcatheter LAAC devices. Endocardial devices include the Watchman, Watchman FLX, and Amplatzer Amulet. The Lariat is the commonly used combined endocardial-epicardial device.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Schematic illustration of the endocardial LAAC approach. A sheath is introduced through the femoral vein and advanced to the right atrium (RA). Through a transeptal puncture, the sheath is advanced to the LAA, where the device is deployed under fluoroscopic and echocardiographic guidance. AO = aorta, LV = left ventricle, RV = right ventricle."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig2.jpeg" height="2186" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Schematic illustration of the endocardial LAAC approach. A sheath is introduced through the femoral vein and advanced to the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>. Through a transeptal puncture, the sheath is advanced to the LAA, where the device is deployed under fluoroscopic and echocardiographic guidance. <i>AO</i> = aorta, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Contraindication for LAAC in a 63-year-old woman who was under evaluation for transcatheter LAAC. (a) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image shows a hypoattenuating filling defect (arrow) in the tip of the LAA. (b) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image obtained 60 seconds later shows persistence of the filling defect (arrow), which is consistent with a thrombus."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig3a.jpeg" height="1353" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Contraindication for LAAC in a 63-year-old woman who was under evaluation for transcatheter LAAC. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image shows a hypoattenuating filling defect (arrow) in the tip of the LAA. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image obtained 60 seconds later shows persistence of the filling defect (arrow), which is consistent with a thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Contraindication for LAAC in a 63-year-old woman who was under evaluation for transcatheter LAAC. (a) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image shows a hypoattenuating filling defect (arrow) in the tip of the LAA. (b) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image obtained 60 seconds later shows persistence of the filling defect (arrow), which is consistent with a thrombus."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig3b.jpeg" height="1353" width="1206" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Contraindication for LAAC in a 63-year-old woman who was under evaluation for transcatheter LAAC. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image shows a hypoattenuating filling defect (arrow) in the tip of the LAA. <b>(b)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image obtained 60 seconds later shows persistence of the filling defect (arrow), which is consistent with a thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. (a) Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). (b) Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. (c) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig4a.jpeg" height="1209" width="1411" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. (a) Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). (b) Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. (c) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig4b.jpeg" height="1209" width="1737" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. (a) Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). (b) Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. (c) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig4c.jpeg" height="1206" width="1000" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Contraindications for placement of hybrid endocardial-epicardial devices in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis reconstructed CT image in a 47-year-old man shows circumferential pericardial calcification (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in a 43-year-old man shows a severe pectus excavatum deformity (arrow) with a Haller index score of 4.5. <b>(c)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 72-year-old man shows a venous bypass graft from the aorta to the obtuse marginal artery (straight arrow), which is situated directly adjacent to the LAA (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="LAA ostium in a 59-year-old man. Oblique 3D volume-rendered endocardial view CT image of the LA (tan) shows that the extent of the ostium of the LAA (blue) is well defined at the posterior and superior aspect, where it is bordered by the Coumadin ridge (straight arrow) that separates the LAA ostium from that of LSPV. Anteroinferiorly, the ostium is ill-defined (curved arrow) at the region of the LA vestibule."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig5.jpeg" height="1687" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. LAA ostium in a 59-year-old man. Oblique 3D volume-rendered endocardial view CT image of the LA (tan) shows that the extent of the ostium of the LAA (blue) is well defined at the posterior and superior aspect, where it is bordered by the Coumadin ridge (straight arrow) that separates the LAA ostium from that of LSPV. Anteroinferiorly, the ostium is ill-defined (curved arrow) at the region of the LA vestibule.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of LAA ostium. (a) Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). (b) Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). (c) En-face view of the ostial plane in b shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig6a.jpeg" height="1004" width="1175" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Measurement of LAA ostium. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). <b>(b)</b> Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> En-face view of the ostial plane in <b>b</b> shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of LAA ostium. (a) Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). (b) Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). (c) En-face view of the ostial plane in b shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig6b.jpeg" height="999" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Measurement of LAA ostium. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). <b>(b)</b> Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> En-face view of the ostial plane in <b>b</b> shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of LAA ostium. (a) Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). (b) Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). (c) En-face view of the ostial plane in b shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig6c.jpeg" height="999" width="1052" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Measurement of LAA ostium. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image of the heart is used to identify the left circumflex coronary artery (arrow). A plane that is perpendicular to the long axis of the left circumflex artery is identified. Multiplanar reformat axes are shown on the long-axis images (blue and green lines). <b>(b)</b> Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle and LAA shows the LAA ostium, which is defined in the plane between the left circumflex artery (straight arrow) and the Coumadin ridge (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> En-face view of the ostial plane in <b>b</b> shows the LAA ostium in cross-section (arrow), where it is measured. The maximum diameter, minimum diameter, perimeter, and area can be measured.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of landing zone and length of LAA for the Watchman device in a 52-year-old man. (a) Vertical long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle (LV) shows how the landing zone for a Watchman device is identified at a distance of 10–20 mm (red dotted line) distal to the Coumadin ridge (arrow). The pink line is the LAA ostium. The landing zone diameter is measured in the plane between this point and the point where the left circumflex artery is located (green line). The length of the LAA is also measured on the same image from the landing zone to the tip of the dominant lobe (blue line). (b) En-face-view CT image shows the cross-sectional view of the landing zone (arrow), where the maximum diameter, minimum diameter, and perimeter are measured."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig7a.jpeg" height="1214" width="1390" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Measurement of landing zone and length of LAA for the Watchman device in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Vertical long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> shows how the landing zone for a Watchman device is identified at a distance of 10–20 mm (red dotted line) distal to the Coumadin ridge (arrow). The pink line is the LAA ostium. The landing zone diameter is measured in the plane between this point and the point where the left circumflex artery is located (green line). The length of the LAA is also measured on the same image from the landing zone to the tip of the dominant lobe (blue line). <b>(b)</b> En-face-view CT image shows the cross-sectional view of the landing zone (arrow), where the maximum diameter, minimum diameter, and perimeter are measured.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of landing zone and length of LAA for the Watchman device in a 52-year-old man. (a) Vertical long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle (LV) shows how the landing zone for a Watchman device is identified at a distance of 10–20 mm (red dotted line) distal to the Coumadin ridge (arrow). The pink line is the LAA ostium. The landing zone diameter is measured in the plane between this point and the point where the left circumflex artery is located (green line). The length of the LAA is also measured on the same image from the landing zone to the tip of the dominant lobe (blue line). (b) En-face-view CT image shows the cross-sectional view of the landing zone (arrow), where the maximum diameter, minimum diameter, and perimeter are measured."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig7b.jpeg" height="1214" width="1258" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Measurement of landing zone and length of LAA for the Watchman device in a 52-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Vertical long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> shows how the landing zone for a Watchman device is identified at a distance of 10–20 mm (red dotted line) distal to the Coumadin ridge (arrow). The pink line is the LAA ostium. The landing zone diameter is measured in the plane between this point and the point where the left circumflex artery is located (green line). The length of the LAA is also measured on the same image from the landing zone to the tip of the dominant lobe (blue line). <b>(b)</b> En-face-view CT image shows the cross-sectional view of the landing zone (arrow), where the maximum diameter, minimum diameter, and perimeter are measured.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurements for the Amulet device in a 52-year-old man. Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle shows the landing zone for the Amulet device, which is measured 12–15 mm distal (dotted red line) to the LAA ostium (pink line). The tip of the Coumadin ridge (arrow) demarcates the posterior boundary of the LAA ostium. The landing zone (green line) is perpendicular to the walls of the LAA. The depth of the LAA (blue line) is measured as a perpendicular line from the center of the LAA ostium to the roof of the LAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig8.jpeg" height="1248" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Measurements for the Amulet device in a 52-year-old man. Long-axis-view CT image of the left ventricle shows the landing zone for the Amulet device, which is measured 12–15 mm distal (dotted red line) to the LAA ostium (pink line). The tip of the Coumadin ridge (arrow) demarcates the posterior boundary of the LAA ostium. The landing zone (green line) is perpendicular to the walls of the LAA. The depth of the LAA (blue line) is measured as a perpendicular line from the center of the LAA ostium to the roof of the LAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="TEE and CT measurements of the LAA ostium. (a) Illustration shows the measurement of the LAA ostium at TEE at four different angles: 0°, 45°, 90°, and 135°. (b) Illustration shows the measurement of the diameter at CT."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig9a.jpeg" height="1007" width="1506" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. TEE and CT measurements of the LAA ostium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the measurement of the LAA ostium at TEE at four different angles: 0°, 45°, 90°, and 135°. <b>(b)</b> Illustration shows the measurement of the diameter at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="TEE and CT measurements of the LAA ostium. (a) Illustration shows the measurement of the LAA ostium at TEE at four different angles: 0°, 45°, 90°, and 135°. (b) Illustration shows the measurement of the diameter at CT."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig9b.jpeg" height="1008" width="1645" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. TEE and CT measurements of the LAA ostium. <b>(a)</b> Illustration shows the measurement of the LAA ostium at TEE at four different angles: 0°, 45°, 90°, and 135°. <b>(b)</b> Illustration shows the measurement of the diameter at CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Windsock-type LAA in a 49-year-old man. Coronal reconstructed CT image shows the windsock type of LAA (arrow), which has a single dominant lobe larger than 4 cm long, with an angle of more than 100° from the ostium. Tiny accessory lobes are seen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig10.jpeg" height="1139" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Windsock-type LAA in a 49-year-old man. Coronal reconstructed CT image shows the windsock type of LAA (arrow), which has a single dominant lobe larger than 4 cm long, with an angle of more than 100° from the ostium. Tiny accessory lobes are seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Chicken wing type of LAA in a 56-year-old woman. (a) Coronal 2D image of a chicken wing–shaped LAA (arrow), in which there is a sharp bend (&lt;100°) in the proximal segment. (b) Measurement of distance from the LAA ostium (pink dotted line) to the bend (red solid line) in a chicken wing type of LAA. Note that the LAA is located directly posterior to the pulmonary trunk (PT), which makes this a contraindication for the hybrid endocardial-epicardial approach. AO = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig11a.jpeg" height="1216" width="1488" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Chicken wing type of LAA in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal 2D image of a chicken wing–shaped LAA (arrow), in which there is a sharp bend (&lt;100°) in the proximal segment. <b>(b)</b> Measurement of distance from the LAA ostium (pink dotted line) to the bend (red solid line) in a chicken wing type of LAA. Note that the LAA is located directly posterior to the pulmonary trunk <i>(PT)</i>, which makes this a contraindication for the hybrid endocardial-epicardial approach. <i>AO</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Chicken wing type of LAA in a 56-year-old woman. (a) Coronal 2D image of a chicken wing–shaped LAA (arrow), in which there is a sharp bend (&lt;100°) in the proximal segment. (b) Measurement of distance from the LAA ostium (pink dotted line) to the bend (red solid line) in a chicken wing type of LAA. Note that the LAA is located directly posterior to the pulmonary trunk (PT), which makes this a contraindication for the hybrid endocardial-epicardial approach. AO = aorta."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig11b.jpeg" height="1216" width="1163" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Chicken wing type of LAA in a 56-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Coronal 2D image of a chicken wing–shaped LAA (arrow), in which there is a sharp bend (&lt;100°) in the proximal segment. <b>(b)</b> Measurement of distance from the LAA ostium (pink dotted line) to the bend (red solid line) in a chicken wing type of LAA. Note that the LAA is located directly posterior to the pulmonary trunk <i>(PT)</i>, which makes this a contraindication for the hybrid endocardial-epicardial approach. <i>AO</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Cactus-type LAA in a 77-year-old woman. Coronal reconstructed CT image shows the cactus type of LAA (arrow), which has a short dominant lobe and small accessory lobes."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig12.jpeg" height="1091" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Cactus-type LAA in a 77-year-old woman. Coronal reconstructed CT image shows the cactus type of LAA (arrow), which has a short dominant lobe and small accessory lobes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Cauliflower-type LAA in a 61-year-old woman. Reconstructed 2D coronal CT image shows the cauliflower type of LAA, which is short and multilobed, without a dominant lobe or bend."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig13.jpeg" height="986" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Cauliflower-type LAA in a 61-year-old woman. Reconstructed 2D coronal CT image shows the cauliflower type of LAA, which is short and multilobed, without a dominant lobe or bend.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Cone type of LAA in a 63-year-old woman. 2D reconstructed coronal CT image shows an LAA with a cone-type anatomy (arrow), in which there is a rapidly tapering transverse diameter from the base to the apex. Because of this steep gradient, a minor alteration in measurement location can lead to a big change in device size."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig14.jpeg" height="1215" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Cone type of LAA in a 63-year-old woman. 2D reconstructed coronal CT image shows an LAA with a cone-type anatomy (arrow), in which there is a rapidly tapering transverse diameter from the base to the apex. Because of this steep gradient, a minor alteration in measurement location can lead to a big change in device size.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Bilobed-type LAA in a 72-year-old woman. 2D reconstructed coronal CT image shows an LAA with a bilobed or whale tail anatomy (arrow). Because of the short proximal portion of the LAA, it is often challenging to implant a device in the common proximal portion. Implantation of two devices may be needed distally in the two lobes."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig15.jpeg" height="1164" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Bilobed-type LAA in a 72-year-old woman. 2D reconstructed coronal CT image shows an LAA with a bilobed or whale tail anatomy (arrow). Because of the short proximal portion of the LAA, it is often challenging to implant a device in the common proximal portion. Implantation of two devices may be needed distally in the two lobes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic" aria-label="Complex LAA anatomy types. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 69-year-old woman shows a complex multilobed anatomy that is extending in different directions. Note that there are multiple implantation angles. (b) Axial CT image in a 63-year-old man shows a large (approximately 6 cm) LAA (arrow), which makes the Lariat device unsuitable for use in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig16a.jpeg" height="1133" width="1090" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Complex LAA anatomy types. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 69-year-old woman shows a complex multilobed anatomy that is extending in different directions. Note that there are multiple implantation angles. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in a 63-year-old man shows a large (approximately 6 cm) LAA (arrow), which makes the Lariat device unsuitable for use in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Complex LAA anatomy types. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 69-year-old woman shows a complex multilobed anatomy that is extending in different directions. Note that there are multiple implantation angles. (b) Axial CT image in a 63-year-old man shows a large (approximately 6 cm) LAA (arrow), which makes the Lariat device unsuitable for use in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig16b.jpeg" height="1133" width="1158" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Complex LAA anatomy types. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 69-year-old woman shows a complex multilobed anatomy that is extending in different directions. Note that there are multiple implantation angles. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image in a 63-year-old man shows a large (approximately 6 cm) LAA (arrow), which makes the Lariat device unsuitable for use in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Accessory lobes proximal to the landing zone in a 71-year-old man. Two-chamber CT image shows the presence of a large accessory lobe (arrow) proximal to the landing zone (black line) with a chicken wing shape. The pink line is the LAA ostium. Implantation of the device in this landing zone would result in incomplete LAA occlusion."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig17.jpeg" height="1062" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Accessory lobes proximal to the landing zone in a 71-year-old man. Two-chamber CT image shows the presence of a large accessory lobe (arrow) proximal to the landing zone (black line) with a chicken wing shape. The pink line is the LAA ostium. Implantation of the device in this landing zone would result in incomplete LAA occlusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the Coumadin ridge in a 39-year-old man. 3D endocardial view of the LA shows the Coumadin ridge (arrow) between the LAA and the LSPV, measuring 6 mm."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig18.jpeg" height="1347" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Measurement of the Coumadin ridge in a 39-year-old man. 3D endocardial view of the LA shows the Coumadin ridge (arrow) between the LAA and the LSPV, measuring 6 mm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Measurement of the Coumadin ridge in a 39-year-old man. Axial CT image shows the measurement (arrow) of the Coumadin ridge in between the LAA and LSPV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig19.jpeg" height="1239" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Measurement of the Coumadin ridge in a 39-year-old man. Axial CT image shows the measurement (arrow) of the Coumadin ridge in between the LAA and LSPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic" aria-label="Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. (a) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. (b) Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. (c) Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig20a.jpeg" height="1434" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic" aria-label="Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. (a) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. (b) Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. (c) Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig20b.jpeg" height="1434" width="1110" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic" aria-label="Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. (a) Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. (b) Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. (c) Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig20c.jpeg" height="1434" width="1355" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Relationship of the LAA to adjacent structures in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Two-chamber reconstructed CT image in a 37-year-old woman shows the left circumflex coronary artery (straight arrow) and the great cardiac vein (curved arrow), which are located inferior to the LAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial oblique CT image in an 82-year-old man shows the sinoatrial nodal artery (straight arrow), originating from the left circumflex artery (curved arrow) and coursing adjacent to the LAA. <b>(c)</b> Axial oblique reconstructed CT image in a 39-year-old man shows a left-sided superior vena cava (arrow), which is located between the LAA and the LSPV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic" aria-label="Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. (a) Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. (b) Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). (c) Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. (d) Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. (e) Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig21a.jpeg" height="1059" width="1134" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic" aria-label="Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. (a) Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. (b) Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). (c) Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. (d) Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. (e) Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig21b.jpeg" height="1059" width="1011" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic" aria-label="Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. (a) Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. (b) Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). (c) Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. (d) Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. (e) Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig21c.jpeg" height="1253" width="1414" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span>. Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic" aria-label="Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. (a) Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. (b) Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). (c) Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. (d) Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. (e) Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig21d.jpeg" height="1253" width="1232" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span>. Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21e" class="graphic" aria-label="Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. (a) Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. (b) Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). (c) Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. (d) Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. (e) Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig21e.jpeg" height="1253" width="1044" aria-labelledby="fig21e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21e</span>. Abnormalities of the interatrial septum in five patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image in a 55-year-old man shows a large secundum type of atrial septal defect (arrow) located in the mid interatrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis CT image in a 71-year-old man shows a patent foramen ovale, with a small jet of contrast material from the left to the right (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Four-chamber CT image in a 49-year-old man shows a large atrial septal aneurysm (arrow), which is diagnosed when the combined excursion of the interatrial septum in systole and diastole is greater than 1.5 cm. <b>(d)</b> Axial CT image in a 36-year-old woman shows lipomatous hypertrophy of the atrial septum (arrows) measuring larger than 20 mm, with characteristic sparing of the fossa ovalis. <b>(e)</b> Sagittal maximum intensity projection CT image in a 51-year-old man shows an atrial septal occluder (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig21e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic" aria-label="Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. (a) Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. (b) Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). (c) Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). CRA = cranial, IAS = interatrial septum, RAO = right anterior oblique."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig22a.jpeg" height="1141" width="1140" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>IAS</i> = interatrial septum, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic" aria-label="Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. (a) Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. (b) Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). (c) Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). CRA = cranial, IAS = interatrial septum, RAO = right anterior oblique."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig22b.jpeg" height="1141" width="1139" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>IAS</i> = interatrial septum, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic" aria-label="Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. (a) Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. (b) Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). (c) Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). CRA = cranial, IAS = interatrial septum, RAO = right anterior oblique."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig22c.jpeg" height="1141" width="1422" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Interatrial septal puncture planning in a 54-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber reconstructed CT image shows the normal appearance of a thinned fossa ovalis (arrow) in the mid atrial septum. <b>(b)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows a virtual guide of the trajectory of the sheath from the septal puncture into the LAA (orange line). <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered 3D CT image of the left atrium shows the virtual guide (solid orange line) and the corresponding fluoroscopic angle (dotted orange line). <i>CRA</i> = cranial, <i>IAS</i> = interatrial septum, <i>RAO</i> = right anterior oblique.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic" aria-label="Coplanar fluoroscopic angles in a 57-year-old man. A coplanar fluoroscopic angulation of the right anterior oblique (RAO) 40/cranial (CRA) 0 view was derived for the plane that is perpendicular to the maximum diameter of the LAA ostium."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig23.jpeg" height="1145" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Coplanar fluoroscopic angles in a 57-year-old man. A coplanar fluoroscopic angulation of the right anterior oblique <i>(RAO)</i> 40/cranial <i>(CRA)</i> 0 view was derived for the plane that is perpendicular to the maximum diameter of the LAA ostium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic" aria-label="3D printing. Flexible 3D printed models of the left atrial appendage in a 52-year-old man before (a) and after (b) placement of a simulated Watchman device (open arrow in b). The adequacy of the Watchman device sizing and positioning can be assessed with the models. The left atrial appendage (white * in a), the inferior pulmonary vein (black solid arrow in a and b), superior pulmonary vein (white solid arrow in a and b), and the mitral valve orifice (black * in a and b) are also shown."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig24a.jpeg" height="1317" width="1365" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. 3D printing. Flexible 3D printed models of the left atrial appendage in a 52-year-old man before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> placement of a simulated Watchman device (open arrow in <b>b</b>). The adequacy of the Watchman device sizing and positioning can be assessed with the models. The left atrial appendage (white * in <b>a</b>), the inferior pulmonary vein (black solid arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), superior pulmonary vein (white solid arrow in a and <b>b</b>), and the mitral valve orifice (black * in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) are also shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic" aria-label="3D printing. Flexible 3D printed models of the left atrial appendage in a 52-year-old man before (a) and after (b) placement of a simulated Watchman device (open arrow in b). The adequacy of the Watchman device sizing and positioning can be assessed with the models. The left atrial appendage (white * in a), the inferior pulmonary vein (black solid arrow in a and b), superior pulmonary vein (white solid arrow in a and b), and the mitral valve orifice (black * in a and b) are also shown."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig24b.jpeg" height="1321" width="1381" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. 3D printing. Flexible 3D printed models of the left atrial appendage in a 52-year-old man before <b>(a)</b> and after <b>(b)</b> placement of a simulated Watchman device (open arrow in <b>b</b>). The adequacy of the Watchman device sizing and positioning can be assessed with the models. The left atrial appendage (white * in <b>a</b>), the inferior pulmonary vein (black solid arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), superior pulmonary vein (white solid arrow in a and <b>b</b>), and the mitral valve orifice (black * in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) are also shown.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. (a) Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. (c) Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig25a.jpeg" height="1170" width="1284" aria-labelledby="fig25a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25a</span>. Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. <b>(c)</b> Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig25a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. (a) Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. (c) Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig25b.jpeg" height="1267" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig25b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25b</span>. Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. <b>(c)</b> Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig25b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25c" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. (a) Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. (c) Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig25c.jpeg" height="1267" width="1274" aria-labelledby="fig25c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25c</span>. Normal CT appearance after placement of a Watchman device in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered 3D reconstruction CT image obtained 60 days after implantation shows the Watchman device (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows no enhancement in the device (arrow), which indicates that endothelialization has occurred, and no peridevice leak. <b>(c)</b> Cross-sectional reconstructed CT image shows the device hubs and normal appearances of a thrombus (arrow) in the device.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig25c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal postprocedural CT appearance after placement of the Lariat device in a 59-year-old woman. Axial CT image shows ligation of the LAA (arrow) and no contrast material opacification of the LAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig26.jpeg" height="1168" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Normal postprocedural CT appearance after placement of the Lariat device in a 59-year-old woman. Axial CT image shows ligation of the LAA (arrow) and no contrast material opacification of the LAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic" aria-label="Device-related thrombus in a 64-year-old woman. Axial CT image shows a hypoattenuating lesion on the surface of the Watchman device (arrow) that persisted in the delayed phase (not shown), which is consistent with a device-related thrombus."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig27.jpeg" height="1094" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Device-related thrombus in a 64-year-old woman. Axial CT image shows a hypoattenuating lesion on the surface of the Watchman device (arrow) that persisted in the delayed phase (not shown), which is consistent with a device-related thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic" aria-label="Peridevice leak in four patients. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. (b) Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. (c) Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. (d) Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig28a.jpeg" height="1011" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Peridevice leak in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. <b>(b)</b> Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. <b>(d)</b> Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic" aria-label="Peridevice leak in four patients. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. (b) Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. (c) Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. (d) Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig28b.jpeg" height="1194" width="1199" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Peridevice leak in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. <b>(b)</b> Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. <b>(d)</b> Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28c" class="graphic" aria-label="Peridevice leak in four patients. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. (b) Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. (c) Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. (d) Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig28c.jpeg" height="1194" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig28c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28c</span>. Peridevice leak in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. <b>(b)</b> Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. <b>(d)</b> Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig28c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28d" class="graphic" aria-label="Peridevice leak in four patients. (a) Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. (b) Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. (c) Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. (d) Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig28d.jpeg" height="1194" width="1274" aria-labelledby="fig28d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28d</span>. Peridevice leak in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reconstructed CT image in a 59-year-old man with a Watchman device shows incomplete sealing of the device in the LAA wall, resulting in a peridevice leak lateral to the device (arrow), which results in free flow of contrast material inside the device. <b>(b)</b> Reconstructed coronal CT image in a 63-year-old man with a Watchman device shows off-axis placement of the device (white arrow) with a peri-device leak laterally (black arrow). There is flow of contrast material in the device (*) and distally in the LAA apex. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in a 47-year-old man shows a large leak measuring 11 mm around the lateral aspect of the device (arrow). Contrast material is also seen in the distal LAA beyond the device. <b>(d)</b> Fabric leak with two contrast channels is seen within the device material (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig28d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic" aria-label="Incomplete closure due to absence of endothelialization in an 80-year-old man 60 days after implantation of a Watchman device. Axial CT image shows the absence of a thrombus and extensive contrast material in the device (arrow), which is consistent with a complete absence of neoendothelialization."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig29.jpeg" height="1194" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span>. Incomplete closure due to absence of endothelialization in an 80-year-old man 60 days after implantation of a Watchman device. Axial CT image shows the absence of a thrombus and extensive contrast material in the device (arrow), which is consistent with a complete absence of neoendothelialization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic" aria-label="Incomplete closure in a 53-year-old man after placement of a Lariat device. Two-chamber CT image shows free flow of contrast material in the LAA (arrow) as the result of incomplete ligation of the LAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200136/asset/images/large/rg.2021200136.fig30.jpeg" height="1072" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span>. Incomplete closure in a 53-year-old man after placement of a Lariat device. Two-chamber CT image shows free flow of contrast material in the LAA (arrow) as the result of incomplete ligation of the LAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200136&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Wolf PA, Abbott RD, Kannel WB. Atrial fibrillation as an independent risk factor for stroke: the Framingham Study. <em>Stroke</em> 1991;22(8):983–988.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/01.STR.22.8.983">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1866765/">PubMed</a></div><div cla